The market of Electric Vehicles in Europe - a python project

Author: Pietro Tegon

The market of EVs in Europe: the evoultion from 2013

Electric vehicles (EVs) have a fascinating history that stretches back to the 1800s. In Europe, early inventors like Hungarys nyos Jedlik, who made one of the first electric motors in 1828, and Englands Thomas Parker, who built practical electric cars in the 1880s, were key players in getting the EV ball rolling. Although EVs were initially popular, they lost out to gasoline-powered cars as those became cheaper and more efficient, thanks largely to Henry Fords assembly line. Fast forward to today, and the scene has changed dramatically. With rising environmental concerns and significant advances in battery technology, EVs are making a strong comeback.

This surge is powered by strict emissions regulations and substantial government incentives, all aimed at promoting greener transportation options. Initially driven by early adopters and environmental policies, the EV market has rapidly expanded, especially in Europe, boosted by advancements in technology, increasing consumer awareness, and robust governmental incentives. Countries such as Germany, France, and the Netherlands have led the charge, contributing to a substantial rise in EV sales and stock. Infrastructure development, particularly charging points, has further facilitated this growth.

As the industry evolves, the focus is shifting towards improving EV stock share, optimizing the ratio of EVs to charging points, and sustaining the momentum of sales growth. The European Union has set a very ambitious objective in this direction: zero CO2 emissions for new passenger cars and light commercial vehicles in 2035. This notebook explores trends and forecasts about future developments in the European EV landscape by analizing data collected from the IEA (International Energy Agency).

Research questions

The questions that will constitute the guidelines which will be followed throughout the notebook are:

  • During the years, which are the countries that led the market (in sales and stock) of EVs?
  • Which are the countries with the best stock ratio for EVs (the countries that have the most electric vehicles compared to the normal ones)?
  • Are the various categories of the data correlated? In what way?
  • How has the market evolved in the years? Have the sales and the stock increased?

Project overview and methodology

The project will be divided in four parts:

  • Part 1: Installing necessary modules

  • Part 2: Data cleaning

  • Part 3: Data combining and reshaping

  • Part 4: Data analisys and visualization

  • Part 5: Forecasting

The data selected will be functional to the answers to the research questions. The method will be quite empirical: the analysis and interpretation of the data will be the basis of the answers. The project is divided in five parts to make the notebook the clearer and easier to read as possible, and include commented code and markdowns that explains the reason behind every step and its result.

eu_countries = ["Austria", "Belgium", "Bulgaria", "Croatia", "Cyprus", "Czech Republic", "Denmark", "Estonia", "Finland", "France", "Germany", "Greece", "Hungary", "Ireland", 
                "Italy", "Latvia",  "Lithuania", "Luxembourg", "Malta", "Netherlands", "Poland", "Portugal", "Romania", "Slovakia", "Slovenia", "Spain", "Sweden"]
# This is a list of all the countries in the EU

eu_data_ssp = sales_stock[sales_stock['region'].isin(eu_countries)] #.isin() method is used to select only the countries that are in the list

eu_data_sales= eu_data_ssp[eu_data_ssp['parameter']=='EV sales'] # In this first cleaning process only the elements with value in the column 'parameter' equal to 'EV sales'
eu_sales= eu_data_sales[eu_data_sales['powertrain'] != 'FCEV'] # We can exclude FCEV (hydrogen powered cars) because they are very rare and are insignificant 
                                                               # compared to the rest of electric vehicles


summed_sales = eu_sales.groupby(['region', 'year'])['value'].sum().reset_index() # This groups EV, BEV and PHEV vehicles and sums their sales to obtain just one value per year

summed_sales.columns = ['region', 'year', 'Total EV Sales'] # The only significant columns are these three: we had only historical data, only one parameter selcted, only one mode
                                                            # and unit: vehicle for all rows.
                                                            #The columns have also been switched and renamed

Part 3 - Data combining and reshaping

Part 4 - Data analisys and visualization

Data analysis

Correlation analysis

Correlation analysis is a statistical technique used to assess the strength and direction of the relationship between two variables. It doesn't necessarily determine causation, but helps identify potential connections within the data. Correlation analysis provides a numerical coefficient (between -1 and +1) that indicates the degree of association between two variables.

A higher positive value means a stronger positive correlation (as one variable increases, the other tends to increase as well). On the other hand, a higher negative value indicates a stronger negative correlation (as one variable increases, the other tends to decrease). A value close to zero suggests little to no linear relationship.

In[17]:
correlation_matrix = final_sscpp[['Total EV Sales', 'Total EV Stock', 'Total Charging Points']].corr()

print(correlation_matrix)

                       Total EV Sales  Total EV Stock  Total Charging Points
Total EV Sales               1.000000        0.956936               0.739016
Total EV Stock               0.956936        1.000000               0.805497
Total Charging Points        0.739016        0.805497               1.000000

As the values of the correlation coefficient suggest, all values have strong positive correlations. The weakest one is the one between sales and total charging points; this could be explained by the fact that sales are a value which starts from 0 every year, while total charging points start from the value of the previous year.

Overview on the best countries for each category

def plot_bar_dual_axis_top_8(year):

    ax2 = ax1.twinx()
    
    sns.barplot(data=df_year_sorted, x='region', y='Total EV Stock', palette='viridis', ax=ax1)
    sns.lineplot(data=df_year_sorted, x='region', y='Total Charging Points', color='r', marker='o', ax=ax2)
    
    ax1.set_title(f'Total EV Stock and Total Charging Points in {year}')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Region')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Total EV Stock')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Total Charging Points')
    
    plt.show()

#Showing the graph for each year

    plot_bar_dual_axis_top_8(i)

This graph shows the relationship between Total EV Stock and Total Charging points. It's important to keep in mind that the scale on the right and the one on the left are different. The correlation between the two categories is clear: even if some countries have a higher ratio than others, the more EVs there are, the more charging points there are. This is an important relationship to consider for the future, because if the quantity of EVs will keep increasing, the charging points will have to do so as well. Countries like the Netherlands are well prepared: they have more charging points than Germany and France with respectively less than a third and less than half electric vehicles. Generally, over time, there was not a significant change in shape of the curve formed by the charging point: this means that they were kept proportionate to the number of vehicles as they were in the first years.

Part 5 - Forecasting

ARIMA models

An ARIMA (AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average) model is a widely used statistical technique for time series forecasting. It combines three components: Autoregression (AR), which uses the relationship between an observation and a number of lagged observations; Integration (I), which involves differencing the observations to make the time series stationary; and Moving Average (MA), which uses the dependency between an observation and a residual error from a moving average model applied to lagged observations. In this notebook, an ARIMA model has been implemented using the statsmodels library, where the ARIMA class is utilized to fit the model to historical data.

In[24]:
# Filter the dataset for years >= 2013 (some countries have data from 2010, but in the next step a dataframe is going to be created with the sum of 
# all sales in a year for each country, and years from 2010 to 2012 would make predictions less reliable)

filtered_df = final_sscpp[final_sscpp['year'] >= 2013]

# Aggregate data by year
df_yearly = filtered_df.groupby('year').agg({
    'Total EV Sales': 'sum',
    'EV Stock Share': 'mean'
}).reset_index()

df_yearly.set_index('year', inplace=True)

# Fit ARIMA model for Total EV Sales
model_sales = ARIMA(df_yearly['Total EV Sales'], order=(1, 1, 1))
model_sales_fit = model_sales.fit()

# Forecast the next years until 2035
forecast_years = list(range(2024, 2036))

# Forecasting for Total EV Sales
forecast_sales = model_sales_fit.get_forecast(steps=len(forecast_years))
forecast_sales_values = forecast_sales.predicted_mean
forecast_sales_ci = forecast_sales.conf_int()

# Create a DataFrame to hold the forecasted values
forecast_df_sales = pd.DataFrame({
    'year': forecast_years,
    'Forecasted EV Sales': forecast_sales_values
})
forecast_df_sales.set_index('year', inplace=True)

# Combine with historical data for plotting
combined_df_sales = pd.concat([df_yearly[['Total EV Sales']], forecast_df_sales])

# Plot the forecasted data for Total EV Sales
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

combined_df_sales['Total EV Sales'].plot(kind='bar', color='blue', ax=ax1, position=0, width=0.4, label='Total EV Sales')
combined_df_sales['Forecasted EV Sales'].plot(kind='bar', color='cyan', ax=ax1, position=1, width=0.4, alpha=0.5, label='Forecasted EV Sales')

# Adding labels and title
ax1.set_ylabel('Total EV Sales')
ax1.set_xlabel('Year')
ax1.set_title('Forecasted Total EV Sales until 2035')
ax1.legend(loc='upper left')

plt.show()

The prediction of this model for the years to come is very interesting. The forecasted sales of electric vehicles are expected to keep growing, but at a slower pace each year. The gap between one column and the following one gets smaller at every step. This means that the growth rate will decline and the sales are expected to stabilize at around 3 million units a year. The total of cars sold in Europe in 2023 was more than 12 million; considering that the number might grow in the next eleven years, if the sales of EVs follow the predicted path, they won't be enough for Europe to successfully complete the objective posed for 2035, because the three million EVs sold will only make up for less than a quarter of the demand.

# Fit ARIMA model for EV Stock Share
model_stock_share = ARIMA(df_yearly['EV Stock Share'], order=(1, 1, 1))
model_stock_share_fit = model_stock_share.fit()

# Forecasting for EV Stock Share
forecast_stock_share = model_stock_share_fit.get_forecast(steps=len(forecast_years))

forecast_df_stock_share = pd.DataFrame({

    'Forecasted EV Stock Share': forecast_stock_share_values
})

# Combine with historical data for plotting
combined_df_stock_share = pd.concat([df_yearly[['EV Stock Share']], forecast_df_stock_share])

# Plot the forecasted data for EV Stock Share
fig, ax2 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

combined_df_stock_share['EV Stock Share'].plot(kind='line', color='red', marker='o', ax=ax2, label='EV Stock Share')
combined_df_stock_share['Forecasted EV Stock Share'].plot(kind='line', color='magenta', marker='x', ax=ax2, linestyle='--', label='Forecasted EV Stock Share')

# Adding labels and title
ax2.set_ylabel('EV Stock Share (%)')
ax2.set_xlabel('Year')
ax2.set_title('Forecasted EV Stock Share until 2035')
ax2.legend(loc='upper left')

plt.show()

This graph shows the forecast of the EV Stock Share. The growth is steady and, according to the prediction, by 2035 we should reach a stock share of almost 25%. This means that 1 in 4 vehicles will be electric. This is an encouraging prediction, explained by the consistency of the sales. An important indicator of the trend of EV Stock Share is the flex there seems to be in 2024: from 2013 to 2023 the graph is convex, while from 2024 there seems to be a chanhe in concavity. This means that the growth rate, even if slowly, is declining and in the future the stock share could experience an extremely low growth or even a decline.

This conclusions do not take into consideration the actual complexity of the problem: it would be very hard to account for all the variables that might come up or completely change in a span of ten years. Policies might completely change, the demand of vehicles might crash due to significant improvements of the public transportation systems...

The results obtained from this predictions just account for the data studied in this notebook, which are still a solid basis on which a prediction can be made.

Conclusions

The data analyzed in this notebook gave an overview of the situation in Europe about electric vehicles and the market around them. It is a sector that is growing at a good pace, in some countries more than others, and it's supposed to experience an even further growth. The pollution coming from combustion-engine vehicles is a serious problem that Europe (and the entire world) is facing and the solution that was proposed is to rely more and more on electric vehicles. The challenge is very complicated, especially because car manifacturers and citizens will have to overcome many economic obstacles: this is probably one of the main reasons why the EV sector is not experiencing an even faster growth. If some additional incentives or laws are not adopted, or a new strategy is not taken into consideration, the growth of this sector could slow down significantly. This doesn't mean that it will not grow: as the predictions showed, both stock and sales are supposed to grow, but at a slower pace. Probably the EV sector won't reach the expected numbers by 2035, but the goal might also be too ambitious.
